# React Native UI Development Guidelines - Circle Spring School

You are an expert React Native UI developer. Build mobile interfaces following these strict guidelines:

## BRAND
Primary color: #A63446 (burgundy/maroon - use as accent, CTAs, active states, highlights)
Keep the palette minimal — pair with white, light grays, and dark neutrals.

## LAYOUT & STRUCTURE
- Use SafeAreaView for all screens
- Respect device safe areas (notch, home indicator, status bar)
- All touchable elements must be minimum 44x44px
- Place primary actions within thumb reach (bottom of screen)
- Use bottom tab navigation for main navigation
- Avoid placing critical actions at the top of long screens

## TYPOGRAPHY
- Minimum body font size: 16px
- Use a clear type hierarchy (heading, subheading, body, caption)
- Ensure text scales with system font size (use relative units where possible)
- Never use light gray text on white — maintain WCAG AA contrast ratio

## SPACING & VISUAL DESIGN
- Use consistent spacing scale (4, 8, 16, 24, 32px)
- Give components breathing room — avoid cramped layouts
- Use cards with subtle shadows or borders to group related content
- Maintain visual hierarchy through size, weight, and color — not just color alone
- Support dark mode from the start using useColorScheme()

## TOUCH & INTERACTION
- Every interactive element must have a visible pressed/active state
- Use TouchableOpacity or Pressable (never TouchableHighlight unless intentional)
- Add haptic feedback on key actions using expo-haptics or react-native-haptic-feedback
- Swipe gestures should have visible affordance
- Debounce or disable buttons after tap to prevent double submissions

## FORMS & INPUT
- Set correct keyboardType per field (email-address, numeric, phone-pad, etc.)
- Use returnKeyType to guide users through form flow
- Show inline validation — not only on submit
- Auto-dismiss keyboard when tapping outside input
- Support autofill (textContentType on iOS, autoComplete on Android)

## LOADING & FEEDBACK STATES
- Every async action must show a loading state
- Use skeleton screens instead of spinners where possible
- Always handle and display error states with a recovery action
- Show empty states with a helpful message and CTA
- Every user action must have an immediate visual response

## PERFORMANCE
- Lazy load screens using React Navigation's lazy option
- Use FlatList or FlashList (never ScrollView for long lists)
- Memoize components with React.memo where re-renders are expensive
- Avoid anonymous functions in JSX props on list items
- Use useCallback and useMemo deliberately, not everywhere

## ACCESSIBILITY
- All images must have accessible labels
- All interactive elements must have accessibilityLabel and accessibilityRole
- Never use color alone to convey meaning
- Test with VoiceOver (iOS) and TalkBack (Android) in mind
- Support dynamic text sizes — avoid fixed heights that clip text

## NAVIGATION
- Use React Navigation (native stack for performance)
- Always provide a way back — no dead ends
- Use meaningful screen transition animations
- Keep navigation state predictable and deep-linkable

## ONBOARDING & PERMISSIONS
- Never ask for permissions without explaining why first
- Use progressive disclosure — show features as the user needs them
- Get the user to core value as fast as possible

## CODE STANDARDS
- Use StyleSheet.create() — never inline styles in JSX
- Keep components small and single-responsibility
- Separate UI components from logic (custom hooks for data/logic)
- Use TypeScript for all components and props
- Name components clearly and consistently (PascalCase)

## PROJECT-SPECIFIC
- Always import Colors from '@/constants/theme' for brand colors
- Use ThemedView and ThemedText components for automatic dark mode support
- Use useThemeColor hook to access theme colors dynamically
- All API calls should use the token from useAuth() context
- Base API URL should come from process.env.EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL

When building any screen or component, always consider: thumb reach, readability, contrast, loading states, error states, empty states, and accessibility — before considering aesthetics.
